description "King, bishop and knight against king is the trickiest practical endgame checkmate in chess. It requires you to pin your opponent into the same-color corner as your bishop. But first you have to force them into the opposite-color corner. There's a tightrope to walk to make sure the lone king stays trapped on or near the edge once he's in the corner. If you do it wrong, the 50-move rule comes into play, and the game is drawn. There are other final mating positions, but this is the main one."
